{
  "texts": [
    "For Image 1 we can see that the host galaxy is the dominant source of extinction, and for images 2, 3, 4 there is a progressively larger contribution from the dust in the lens galaxy, with correspondingly higher values of the color excess.",
    "Figure taken from Dhawan et al. (2020) differential reddening as the various images travel through different regions of the lensing galaxy (i.e., infer the differences in A V between the multiple SN images).",
    "Multi-wavelength observations of the lens system will also allow one to probe variations in R V for different sightlines traversed by the multiple SN images (our own Milky Way shows variations in R V; Fitzpatrick and Massa 2007; Schlafly et al. 2016).",
    "Corrections for differential extinctions in systems of strongly lensed SNe Ia is crucial to also make use of their standard candle nature to infer the lensing magnification.",
    "Exploiting the well-known color evolution of SNe Ia, Dhawan et al. (2020) were able to infer both the extinction in the lensing galaxy for iPTF16geu, along with the common color excess from attenuation in the host galaxy using multi-band images from HST, as shown in Fig. 13."
  ]
}